Russia and Turkey: an alliance of the “incompatible”?
It was a gesture that ended in crisis.
The leaders of Russia and Turkey met on Tuesday to shake hands and formally end an eight-month-long war of words and economic sanctions.
But while Vladimir Putin welcomed the Turkish counterpart in the luxurious hall of the palace in St. Petersburg, I had the impression that Ankara wanted this reconciliation more.
There was a handshake, yes.
But Putin was not smiling, and there was hardly any warmth in him, even by his measured standards.
Recep Tayyip Erdogan, on the other hand, has repeatedly spoken of his “dear friend” Mr. Putin – five times, according to one report.
I didn't count it.
He also promised that relations with Russia will not only return to their pre-crisis level, but will be even better.
The next day, a local newspaper reported that Erdogan had acted as if nothing bad had ever happened.
I think his enthusiasm was the exact opposite.
But the persistent cold that radiated from Putin showed that the Russian leader has not forgotten anything.
The real cause of the crisis was the first thing he mentioned in his opening speech: the downing of a Russian fighter jet by Turkey on the Syrian border.
Moscow’s reaction was furious.
Putin struck around him and accused Ankara of stabbing Moscow in the back.
The scandal was all the more so because it came from an alleged friend.
It will be difficult, perhaps even impossible, to rebuild true trust.
Russian public opinion has also changed since December.
For months, state-controlled media have been conducting a massive nationwide campaign against Ankara.
Suddenly, it seemed like the Turks were responsible for everything.
More serious were the accusations from top state officials that Erdogan’s own family benefited from the illegal oil trade in parts of Syria controlled by the so-called Islamic State.
He vehemently denied this.
But in St. Petersburg, the official message came that it was time to move on.
After all, this meeting only happened because Putin was given an apology he had asked for from President Erdogan.
Russia could have declared some kind of victory.
For Ankara, the benefits of declaring a ceasefire are clear.
First of all, Erdogan was almost deposed in a failed coup last month and therefore needs all his friends.
The repeated terrorist attacks in Turkey visibly shocked him as well.
There is also an economic motive.
Russia’s sanctions have had a severe impact, notably the cancellation of charter flights that carry several million Russian tourists to the Turkish coast every year.
This number has decreased by almost 90%.
As far as Russia is concerned, tour operators and charter companies are sure to take a break when flights resume.
They earn on Mediterranean tourism at the end of the season.
Even this week, state television has promised cheaper fruits and vegetables when imports of agricultural commodities from Turkey are allowed again.
"Tourists there, tomatoes back here," as reported in the Vedemosti newspaper.
The visit, however, had additional political value for Moscow.
Ankara is angry with the West for what it considers a weak response to the coup attempt.
Moreover, the long-standing hostility of the protracted EU accession talks and Putin’s entry – who is eager to take advantage of the cooling and break Turkey’s ties with the West.
The Russian leader certainly gained bonus points when Ankara asked him for help from the elected authorities after the coup attempt.
You have to understand that for Moscow, which has a deep-rooted fear of regime change, this is a given.
So the summit in this pompous seaside palace of Russia and Turkey allowed me to demonstrate what one analyst described to me as an “alliance of incompatibility”: how the forces of two countries that feel rejected and exploited by the West unite.
However, despite the fact that they have publicly shown mutual reconciliation, there are fundamental differences between the two countries.
The first is Syria, where Moscow recently played the role of a peacemaker, but where Russia and Turkey stand on opposite sides.
It could be said that after almost three hours of initial talks, the two presidents said at a press conference that they had not even mentioned the issue.
