French court refuses to tear down shops in Jungle refugee camp
A French court has rejected an order by Calais authorities to demolish dozens of makeshift shops and restaurants in the jungle camp, home to thousands of refugees.
In a court hearing this week, Calais authorities argued that the state should be able to shut down a total of 72 makeshift stores where people inside the camp sell goods from cigarettes to energy drinks, offer haircuts, sell tea for 50 cents in makeshift restaurants or basic dishes for a few euros.
The prefect's office in Calais argued that the sites need to be demolished because they represent a parallel economy that does not pay taxes and because they imply fire hazards and health risks.
Humanitarian organizations in the court said shops and restaurants were vital and that free meals offered by state-sponsored associations and other groups did not provide food supplements for the growing numbers of refugees in the camp.
Controversial makeshift shops and restaurants often provide shelter and free food to people in need.
The Lille court ruled that there was no legal basis to prevent people from operating 72 temporary businesses, but said the prefect’s objections were “completely understandable.”
Judge Jean-François Molla said that grocery stores, cafes and restaurants have a much bigger role to play than just serving food to people who “live in extremely desperate conditions.”
He said the premises provide quiet places for refugees and volunteers to meet.
One of the places threatened with demolition was a cafe in the camp, Jungle Book Kids, run by a non-profit organization that offers 200 meals a day, lessons of English and French, and asylum counselling for hundreds of unaccompanied minors at risk in the camp.
More than 170,000 people have signed a petition to protect the “children’s” cafe.
The Guardian received a letter saying that closing the café “would be a disaster for these children, some of whom are only 8 years old.”
The charity Help Refugess and L'Auberge des Migrants estimated on Friday that the number of refugees in the camp after a steep increase in arrivals during the summer has risen to more than 9,000 - the highest ever.
