Secretary-General of the National Broadcasting and Telecommunications Commission, Takorn Tantasith, said there would be no exceptions.
The national telecoms regulator introduced a plan to sell SIM cards exclusively to foreigners in early August.
The new measure, which will allow monitoring of their location, the authorities intend to introduce within six months.
According to Tantasith, this is a means of maintaining national security, which will allow to solve criminal activities committed by foreigners.
In addition, so-called tourist SIMs are also intended to help detect people who exceed the allowed length of stay.
Within six months, a special SIM for foreigners should appear alongside the SIM intended exclusively for Thais.
The difference will be the tracking function, which will be permanently turned on for cards intended for people without a Thai passport.
It won't be possible to turn it off.
"This feature is not for Thais because we can always easily track them," Tantasith added.
It should be added that in Thailand, subscriptions are not anonymous as in the Czech Republic.
The seller requires a proof of identity.
On the other hand, for several years, one of the operators gave a free start-up SIM to tourists at airports.
They were completely anonymous.
Ten telecommunications regulators from other Asian countries, including Malaysia and Singapore, are considering introducing the same measure as Thailand.
They also currently have a mandatory SIM registration, but the legal use of the tracking system is not possible.
However, the planned measure does not imply an obligation for foreigners to acquire a local operator when entering the SIM country.
Of course, they can use roaming services with their own home SIM, in which case the Thai authorities will be short on them.
The operators of a given country only know the relevant network information after crossing the border, i.e. after the SIM has logged in to their network.
They have a phone number, but no information about the owner.
However, the difference in roaming prices from the rates of local operators is so abysmal that even most tourists during their stay in Thailand begin to look for local SIMs.
The authorities’ attempts to supervise the movement of foreigners have received immediate criticism from foreigners living in Thailand.
Tantasith reassures the situation and, in connection with the protection of privacy, compares the upcoming system to the obligation to provide a residence address in immigration documents.
In addition, if necessary, the police will need a court order to track a specific person.
Any misuse of the system will be subject to an unspecified penalty.
“If the service provider monitors the SIM location without a court order, it will be charged with a crime,” Tantasith added.
In addition, the system should maximize the use of prepaid cards.
While a specific number will currently only be recycled after the 90-day period after which the SIM did not log in to the network, the number could be recycled after 15 days if you leave Thailand.
