The condition was sufficient parking spaces and an elevator in the house, which essentially disqualified the older development.
Not to mention problematic acoustics in old houses, problems with swinging the floor, high energy intensity and the like.
The condition was also large terraces, which the old building is not able to offer.
More interesting visits can be found in the magazine Modern flat.
The entire interior was designed for you by architect Lenka Langerová and her colleague Kamila Poláková from Artiga studio.
Why did you contact them?
Would you recommend working with an expert to anyone?
We would recommend cooperation with the architect to everyone if he is designing an apartment from the beginning, because it is a very complex technical process.
The second level is the interior design itself: designers have a much better idea of the range of possible materials and, based on the client's wishes, are able to appropriately harmonize the interior.
We worked with architect Lenka Langerová on our mountain apartment, then based on the personal recommendation of another client, and given that everything worked well, it was a clear choice for us when renovating our new apartment in Vinohrady.
What were your practical and aesthetic requirements?
We wanted a generous social and living space with adequate facilities for a family of four conceived as a modern, but not cool interior.
The priority was to achieve the connection of the apartment with the terraces and to realize the intelligent control of the household.
And of course, the quality of execution had to be monitored.
Did you leave everything to the experts, or did you yourself interfere with the final form of the interior?
We approved all designs, including technical drawings and samples of materials, but the design always came from architects.
At the beginning, we set out what we expected from the design and showed some of the interior elements that we would like to incorporate into the design, such as carpets or paintings.
I think that our collection of mostly Czech authors, including works by Karel Malich, Karel Vysil, Václav <0xC5><0xA0>pála or Otto Gutfreund, helped the architect to orient herself in our taste.
Also, the combination of black, white and walnut wood was the architect’s idea as well as individual pieces of furniture, walls, floor, lighting, carpets, textiles, art, etc. We then verified together with visualizations that everything fits together.
Were there any complications during the realization, because of which you had to give up the original ideas or, on the contrary, take on new ones?
Perhaps only in the initial phase of the project, when we came to the construction site at the moment when it was first possible to climb to the height of our floor, and found that the views we planned, in fact, shield the surrounding buildings.
Then we literally changed the layout overnight from the ground up.
Granite was used on the kitchen line and on the cladding of the fireplace wall.
The interior is dominated by wooden surfaces complemented by leather, for example, on the upholstery of the dining and bar chairs Norma by Arper.
How would you characterize the interior?
Are you making any changes or is there something you would like to have differently today?
I believe that this is a modern airy interior, which primarily fulfills its purpose.
We are not going to make changes, most of the changes after moving in took place in the level of shielding and occupancy of the terraces.
Perhaps the only reproach is to the floor, when the walnut wood turns out to be too delicate for a household with a dog.
Word of architects, Ing. arch. Lenka Langerová and MgA. Kamila Hornychová, author of the realization.
