You are not negative compared to the French, says a Muslim woman living in Prague.
You're from France.
Where did you live before you moved to Prague?
My parents are from Algeria.
I was born in the south of France, near the Spanish border.
I've moved a lot.
I lived in Toulouse, Lyon and Marseille.
I studied journalism in France, which led me to work in a magazine.
Why did you decide to move out of the country?
I was starting to feel like I was suffocating in France.
I just didn't want to live there anymore.
Mainly because of the atmosphere between people.
I think every Frenchman is very negative.
People in France are negatively inclined in general, but it has gotten worse lately.
It is interesting that you mention negativity.
This is how some people evaluate the Czech character.
Believe me, you're not negative compared to the French.
Some people may not feel this way when they come to France, because they do not perceive it as such as tourists.
But it was too much for me.
A big issue is money.
People feel that they have little money, and the minimum wage in France is fifteen hundred euros, which in my opinion is enough.
Now there is a problem with the behavior of people towards Muslims.
That's completely incomprehensible to me.
For example, in the street where I lived, my non-Muslim neighbor began to look me over the shoulder just because I was Muslim.
It's like I'm some kind of evil.
That’s why I didn’t feel good in France.
My family stayed there.
So you decided to go to another country.
Why did you choose the Czech Republic?
I was looking for a job practically anywhere else and I came across a vacancy at Air France here in Prague.
I have to admit that I did not know Prague at all in the beginning.
I knew something about the Czech Republic, my dad even told me about what was happening in Czechoslovakia, but I didn’t know what to expect from Prague.
I've been here three years now, and I can't imagine not living here.
Was it a big difference when you moved from France to Prague?
Especially because of a different atmosphere.
Maybe it’s because I don’t speak Czech, so I can’t capture any negative reactions or insults, but I feel that people here are more free.
That I could do anything, dress anything, and no one would judge me.
In France, someone is always looking at you in an unpleasant way, even when you have special clothes and so on.
I started to feel really free in Prague.
I don't think the Praguers care about such things.
Where do you work now?
After working at Air France, I worked for a travel website for a while.
Then one of my friends and I started a website where people offer and search for shared housing.
We are currently operating only in Prague, but we would like to extend this to the whole of Central Europe.
Do you have any Czech friends in Prague?
I have two very close friends who are half Czechs, and two other Czech friends.
I have to say that another specificity of Czechs is that they initially keep more distance.
They don't let anyone get close to their body.
That's quite a difference from where I grew up.
In the south, everyone hugs and kisses their cheeks.
It's different here, but I understand that it's a cultural thing, so I'm trying to adapt.
You mentioned that you don't speak Czech.
Is the language barrier a problem?
On the contrary, I have it quite simple in Prague, because probably everyone here speaks English.
Even in the evening or in the grocery store.
I would love to learn English, but I don’t have that much time.
And by the fact that everyone can communicate at least a little bit in English, I do not have such a need to learn the language quickly.
And every time I have a problem, there's someone who can help me.
Have you encountered any negative reactions?
Is it because you are a Muslim?
No, not really.
Perhaps it is also because I work in an international environment that is more tolerant.
One experience comes to mind.
My manager, a Czech, once told me about the French football team and said something in the sense: They are not French, they are Africans.
I'm pretty touched by that.
But that someone would have a problem with me being a Muslim, that hasn't happened to me yet.
Even though a colleague once warned me about some anti-Muslim demonstrations.
He told me not to go downtown, that I'd be cursed.
Anti-Muslim demonstrations are partly linked to terrorist attacks.
How does the current situation affect you?
Are you afraid that something similar to Paris, Nice or Brussels could happen in Prague?
I feel safe in Prague.
But the problem is that nowadays anything can happen anywhere.
Until recently, I could not have imagined that such a thing would happen in France.
And it is not just about Muslims.
Islam does not recognize violence at all.
For me, people who kill are not Muslims.
The Koran says that man has no right to kill because he is not God.
How do you feel when terrorists protect your faith?
It's very hard.
I feel shame and guilt, even if I shouldn't feel that way.
I try not to follow the violence reports too much, but every time I read something, I feel the need to apologize for something that isn't really my fault.
I'm a completely different person, so why should I apologize for the terrorists?
We met at Ji<0xC5><0x99>ího z Pod<0xC4><0x9B>brad Square.
On Wednesday, Czech Muslims and Christians protested against the violence.
Did you register it?
I didn't know about that.
But I understand that these people feel the need to prove that they don't agree with violence.
I don't think they have to do something like that.
Why should they feel guilty for something they didn't do?
Do you meet other Muslims in Prague?
My colleagues are, for example, from Egypt and other Muslim countries.
They're a little more religious than I am, so sometimes we have a pretty wild discussion about Islam because we all see it a little differently.
I come from France, so I went through a different education, maybe they learned Islam in school.
We have different approaches, but we respect each other.
People sometimes associate Islam with the subordinate status of women.
How do you see it?
I don’t feel inferior in any way.
Rather the other way around.
I am a woman, I have strength.
It also means that you don’t wear a headgear.
The hijab?
This is mainly due to the way I was raised.
My mother, for example, is a true Muslim.
He prays five times a day, but he just doesn't wear a scarf.
She always taught me that faith is a purely personal thing.
It depends on how everyone interprets it.
When a person reads the Quran, he should make his own opinion about these things.
So when I read a passage in the Qur’an that says that God told the Prophet to hide his wives from the eyes of others, I said to myself, I am not the Prophet’s wife, so why should I hide?
On the other hand, I respect that, and when I travel to Iran or Saudi Arabia, where scarves are required, I take it.
Are you planning to stay in Prague?
So far, yes.
I've never felt so good anywhere else.
I’ve been thinking about Poland for a while, but I’m fine in Prague.
I can even imagine raising my own children here.
Prague is an ideal city for this.
