Its infrastructure has improved dramatically - there is even a new suburban train in the capital, Addis Ababa.
And the streets of the city are typically quiet, safe and clean.
However, Ethiopia can hardly be described as a model of democracy - human rights organizations are constantly talking about government repression - the opposition in the country has been suppressed, dissidents have been effectively silenced.
Many were expelled, imprisoned, killed or driven far into the desert.
However, that may change.
“When you choke people and they have no choice but to protest, they break through,” said Seyoum Teshome, a lecturer at a university in central Ethiopia.
All young people are protesting.
A whole generation has been protesting.
The complaints are many and relate to everything from land disputes to absolute control over the power of the ruling coalition.
After last year’s election, which has been widely criticized, the ruling party and its allies have won the last seat held by the opposition and now control 100 percent of parliament.
At the same time, the pressure on the border with Eritrea is increasing, and the conflict along this imprecisely marked, disputed border claimed hundreds of lives in June.
Anylits fear that separatist groups that have been more or less repressed over the past years, such as the Oromian Liberation Front or the Ogaden National Liberation Front, may try to exploit the confusion and rearm themselves.
There are several factors that explain why now, after years of smoking under the surface, these bitter feelings have reignited.
The first is seemingly harmless: smartphones.
Many Ethiopians have been able to communicate through social networks only in the last few years, when cheaper smartphones have become commonplace and the provision of Internet services has improved.
And even if the government bans access to Facebook or Twitter, as is usually the case especially during protests, many people can still communicate via Internet proxies that hide the location of these people.
Several young Ethiopians spoke about how they were gathering for the protests.
There is also greater solidarity between the Oroms and the Amhars, the two largest ethnic groups in Ethiopia.
The Oroms and Amhars are not natural allies.
For centuries, Amharic peoples, mostly from the Christian highlands of Ethiopia, excelled in politics and trade, and exploited the Oroms, many of whom are Muslims and live in the lowlands.
But that's also changing.
"We are on the way to a united leadership," Mulatu Gemech, the leader of the Oroms, said.
The largest protests took place in areas inhabited by Amhara and Orom.
Many Amharic and Oromo believe that Ethiopia is unjustly dominated by members of the Tigray ethnicity, who make up about 6% of the population and control the military, intelligence, trade and politics.
The third cause of the unrest is the death of Meles Zenawi.
Zenawi, the former leader of the rebels, was Ethiopia's prime minister for 17 years until his death in 2012, when he succumbed to an unspecified illness.
He was considered a tactical genius, a man who could see around the corner.
Analysts say he was particularly skilled at detecting early signs of dissatisfaction and using envoys to process and win opponents to his side.
“The current regime lacks basic knowledge,” said Abdi, a conflict analyst.
The new Prime Minister of Ethiopia, Hailemariam Desalegn, was pulled out of relative obscurity in order to replace Zenawi.
Unlike Zenawi, who came from the Tigray region of northern Ethiopia, Hailemariam comes from the south.
Analysts say he has no confidence in Tigris-controlled security services.
Many fear that the result will be further bloodshed.
The last time Ethiopia experienced such unrest was in 2005, after thousands of people protested against what analysts described as elections that the government blew and then stole.
A tough crackdown followed, during which many protesters were killed - albeit less than in recent months - and this period of unrest passed relatively quickly.
Development experts praised Ethiopia’s leaders for visionary infrastructure planning such as the new suburban train and measurable progress in the fight against poverty.
However, it is quite clear that the gradual growth of disputes within the Ethiopian government has not stopped this.
And there is a dangerous ethnic formation.
Last month, protesters in the Amharic city of Gondar attacked Tigris-owned businesses, and resentment against Tigris on social media is becoming more common.
Analysts say the protests put the U.S. and other Western allies in an awkward position.
The U.S. government is using Ethiopia as a drone base for overflights over neighboring Somalia, although it recently said the base was closed.
While the West clearly wants to support democracy, at the same time it does not want its ally to fall apart in an already volatile area.
"That," said Abdi, "is a very sharp edge of the blade."
