Depressed food from the time of crisis - in "Square Meal"
Shortly after taking office in March 1933, Franklin Delano Roosevelt sat in the Oval Office and ate lunch.
President Roosevelt, the gourmet, enjoyed a selection of 5th Avenue dishes, such as goose buns and Maryland tortoise soup.
But his menu for the day was more modest: diabolical eggs in tomato sauce, mashed potatoes, and plum pudding as dessert.
"It was an act of cooking solidarity with the people who suffered," said Jane Ziegelman.
Her husband Andrew Coe added, “It was also a message to Americans about how to eat.”
The couple, who live in Brooklyn Heights, focuses on gastronomic history.
Andrew Coe’s last book, Chop Suey, was about Chinese cuisine in America, while Jane, in her book, 97 Orchard, tells the life story of a house on the Lower East Side through food.
Their new collaborative work "A Square Meal", which will be published by Harper on Tuesday, is a history of American cuisine during the Great Depression.
They themselves showed cooking solidarity and met with a reporter for dinner at Eisenberg’s sandwich shop, a small, sprawling buffet in the Flatiron district that has been in operation since the crisis, since 1929.
Jane, 54, ordered cream cheese and a sandwich with chopped olives, Andrew, 57, ate turkey, mashed potatoes, and stirred vegetables.
