"The meatballs were very popular," said Miss Ziegelman.
Peanut, liver and bean meatballs were sold.
They were made from that admixture and other cheap foods that set the ingredient.
Imagine the amount of peanuts you would have to eat for dinner.
Andrew Coe grinned.
"They'd be like lead in your stomach," he said.
In the years before the crisis, American cuisine, especially in rural areas, was served in the form of a buffet of what you eat.
Teams of women cooked for the farm workers, and freshly baked cake was served for breakfast, lunch, and dinner.
It was the Americans who sent food to starving Europeans during World War I. “A Square Meal” tracks how the nation dealt with the fact that it was suddenly not a land of abundance.
“It was a time when food became a central, feared point for the American people,” Coe said, explaining why he and his wife decided to write about it.
Equally feared was the new budget diet: Mysterious foods, such as meatballs and casseroles, casseroles as “an amazing way to use the leftovers,” Ziegelman noted, as cooks could hide unsightly ingredients under a layer of creamy sauce.
Fresh fruit was replaced by cheaper dried fruit.
Meat - for many years the focal point of American food - has become a cost-effectively allocated luxury.
The strange mixtures, which were supposed to serve as a calorie and nutritional filling, had priority over taste or even common sense when cooking.
During research for a book that contains recipes, Miss Ziegelman prepared a time-honored dish of roasted onions stuffed with peanut butter.
"It wasn't a favorite addition to the dinner table," Andrew Coe said.
Jane Ziegelman said, “It was surreal.”
Peanut butter and roasted onions do not go together.
It was typical of a lot of homemade recipes.
As never before and never since, domestic economists—among them Louise Stanley, sheriff of the Federal Bureau of Home Economics from 1923 to 1943—managed the country’s eating habits.
They published recipes and articles in newspapers and magazines, encouraged women to take the reins of the budget, and turned things like creamy spaghetti with carrots into tasty dishes.
The book "A Square Meal" is a celebration of historical delicacies.
First of all, desserts were created in response of the government to its hungry citizens, such as the pose of President Herbert Hoover "I'll have a cake".
While publicly praising the simple Iowa farming cuisine of his childhood, he ate like the chosen millionaire he became.
"He liked to eat continental cuisine, like fish with cucumber sauce," Andrew Coe said.
He was eating in an almost dressed room, wearing a tuxedo.
He was incredibly old-fashioned.
President Roosevelt would probably have made the same mistake if his wife Eleanor hadn’t made him take an example with his own stomach.
As the book relates, Mrs. Roosevelt hired a housewife who was not interested in taste at all. This led to the White House being “not only served almost the hottest meal in all of Washington, but also the most disappointingly prepared.”
Many of the eating habits of the crisis disappeared as soon as the country got back on its feet.
The link has remained in our constant exploration of calories and nutritional values, says Ms. Ziegelman, and in the way science is applied to cooking.
The couple say that while writing the book, they better understood Ms. Ziegelman’s mother’s eating habits – for example, why she couldn’t throw away food.
"She was really afraid of wasting food," Andrew Coe said.
Ziegelman recalled, "It made people sick."
There was an accident with wreaths.
When Eisenberg's tables were clean, she and Mr. Coe took out the dessert they had prepared at home: the plum dessert President Roosevelt ate for lunch.
