NASA's climate model: Venus was once habitable
According to NASA's new climate model, Venus was once habitable.
Scientists at NASA’s Goddard Institute for Space Studies have developed a model for studying Venus using tools and algorithms similar to those used by climate scientists.
The model was designed to determine whether Venus, whose surface is hot, waterless and saturated with CO2, could once have had conditions similar to those on Earth.
Scientists have previously suggested that the low rotation speed of Venus can be explained by its dense atmosphere.
According to the latest simulations, however, it seems that Venus could once boast a thin Earth-like atmosphere while rotating slowly.
The model also dealt with the earlier topography of Venus.
The planet probably had areas drier than Earth, but it once had enough water and geographic diversity to rule life and provide protection against rapid evaporation.
Venus used to use the sun, which was 30 percent subdued.
“In a simulation of the GISS model, Venus during its slow rotation exposes its daily side to the sun for almost two months at a time,” explains GISS scientist Anthony Del Genio in a new report.
This is how the surface heats up and rain forms, creating a dense layer of clouds that act like an umbrella and protect the surface from too much solar heat.
The result is a climate with average temperatures that are actually slightly lower than those currently on Earth.
The model assembled a story of Venus similar to evolution previously hypothetically assembled by planetary scientists.
Although Venus was probably habitable in the past -- over several billion years -- it was exposed to too much heat and ultraviolet radiation.
Its oceans evaporated and water vapor was burned by ultraviolet light.
Hydrogen escaped, and all that remained was a dense atmosphere of carbon dioxide with the deadly effect of a greenhouse gas -- that's Venus as we know it today.
The researchers published their findings from the new climate model of Venus in the journal Geophysical Research Letters.
