Many of the stars in the cluster are now reaching maturity and formed more than 125 million years ago.
Now it turns the fastest.
At moments of maximum rotation speeds, these teenage stars release huge amounts of stellar wind.
Because these winds move along the magnetic fields of stars, they have a slowing effect on them.
As the star ages, its speed of rotation slows down.
Kepler measures the speed of rotation of each star by measuring the time between discovering recognizable points on stars -- similar to sunspots.
According to the latest data on rotational speeds, larger stars rotate more slowly than less massive stars.
Rebull compares stars to dancers, the bigger ones make pirouettes slower than the smaller ones.
"In the 'ballet' of the Pleiades, we see that the slower-moving stars are more massive, while the fastest-moving ones are usually very light stars," Rebull said.
Because the Pleiades cluster is so close, it serves as an ideal space laboratory for comparing the quality of stars and the speed of rotation.
"The Pleiades provide us with an anchor for theoretical models of stellar rotation in both directions, in both younger and older stars," Rebull said.
There’s still a lot we want to know about how, when and why stars slow down their rotational speed, so to speak, “hanging their dancing boots to a nail.”
Rebull and her colleagues detailed the latest analysis of the Pleiades' rotational speeds in three studies that will soon be published in the Astronomical Journal.
Is a Qualification Agreement Necessary?
If I did not apply, then the qualification agreement would not be concluded and after a few months I could transfer to another hospital?
Is it even possible to work after graduation without registering for specialization education?
My point is that in the field in which I would like to work, there is now a vacancy only in a slightly more distant hospital, but in about six months there could be a vacancy in another one where I would like to work later.
I have no idea how to deal with the situation for about six months, the question continues.
Mgr. Lenka Vlková responds.
No legal regulation provides for an obligation to conclude a qualification agreement with the employer - a hospital.
A qualification agreement is a legal institution governed by the Labour Code and may be concluded between an employee and an employer in order to ensure reimbursement of costs incurred in increasing or deepening the employee’s qualification.
In the field of health, long-term pressure is being exerted not to conclude these agreements with a view to ensuring the mobility of health workers, and not all hospitals currently require this agreement.
According to Act No. 95/2004 Coll., on the conditions for obtaining and recognising professional competence and specialised competence to exercise the medical profession of a doctor, dentist and pharmacist, it is explicitly true that participation in specialised training is considered to be a deepening of qualifications (not to increase it).
This means that a qualification agreement can be concluded according to the Labour Code only if the costs are at least CZK 75,000.
There is no legal regulation or obligation to apply for specialization training.
The law only lays down the conditions for application for inclusion in the field of specialization education.
However, according to the law, a doctor is entitled to exercise the profession of a doctor already by completing the necessary university studies, although under the conditions laid down by law (under the professional supervision of a doctor with specialized competence in the relevant field).
The law provides for a situation where professional experience completed in another field of specialization can be included in the specialization training of a doctor, if its content and scope correspond to the relevant educational program.
Theoretically, it would be possible to count the time worked elsewhere, which would correspond to the situation of the interviewer.
However, given the fact that I do not know the circumstances of this case, it is advisable to consult the relevant department of the Ministry of Health (Department of Science and Medical Professions), since the Ministry of Health legally provides a consultancy and consulting service related to the inclusion in the specialisation training and its course.
The advisory service is also provided free of charge by the Czech Medical Chamber, of which every doctor must be a member.
Doctors in Syria's Aleppo region are calling for U.S. intervention.
The United States has made no effort to end the siege (the rebel parts of the city by government troops) and has not used its influence to enforce the protection of civilians, according to a letter to the White House.
“We don’t need tears, compassion, or even prayers; but we desperately need to create a no-fly zone over eastern Halab to stop the attacks, and we need international action to ensure that Halab is not encircled again,” the doctors said.
Russian forces supporting the army loyal to President Bashar al-Assad have announced that they will stop strikes in the Halab area every day for three hours from today to allow safe passage for humanitarian convoys.
From 9:00 to 12:00 CEST all military activities, airstrikes and artillery fire should be stopped.
U.N. humanitarian chief Stephen O'Brien welcomed the move, but said a two-day ceasefire was needed.
According to the AFP, 15 of the 35 doctors operating in the eastern part of Alab, which is controlled by the rebels, turned to Obama in a letter.
During the five-year war, they witnessed the violent, cruel deaths of countless patients, friends and colleagues.
The world looks at how complex Syria is, but it does little to protect us.
Recent offers to evacuate the population from the Syrian regime and Russia sound like lightly veiled threats, pediatricians, surgeons and other doctors said.
Doctors said there had been 42 attacks on medical facilities in Syria in the past month, including 15 on hospitals where they work.
The saddest thing is that we have to decide who lives and who dies.
Small children come to the emergency room with such serious injuries that we have to choose among them those who are most likely to survive.
And sometimes we do not even have the necessary material to help them, the doctors described.
Two weeks ago, four newborns suffocated when an explosion cut off the oxygen supply to their incubators.
They were gasping for breath, and then their lives were over—before they could really begin, they recalled.
An army loyal to President Bashar al-Assad, backed by Russian forces, has surrounded the rebel-held eastern part of Aleppo in recent weeks, leaving more than 200,000 people without food.
The rebels, who are under constant strikes from the Russian and Syrian air forces, managed to break through the encirclement and launch a counteroffensive on Saturday after three weeks.
Both sides then added reinforcements in and around the city.
